Write an expression that describes the total hours that it would take 4 students to complete the large project if they worked 3 hours per day.  Use the properties of algebra to express your answer.<n>Output: P=4*H+1, so ((4*H1 +1)/3*2) = 2*4*H1 + 2<n>2(4*H1+1) = 4*8H1 +2<n>4H +4 = 2H1 +2<n>2H = H1-2, so H=H1-2, thus H1=3H, so H=H-3, so total hours of the project would be H=((H1-3)*4)+3 = (3H1/4)*4 +3<n>and since H is H1/4, H1 =4H (3H1/3H4) + 3
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What are students trying to do? Choices:  A: study philosophy B: become adult C: ask questions D: further education E: study together<n>Output:		When students study a subject they are  studying that subject.<n>Therefore the students are studying philosophy<n>So the final answer  is A<n><n>Input:A friend of mine is leaving on a camping trip and needs to have everything packed up for me.  He has 5 pairs of socks, 3 pairs of long pants, and 4 pairs of shorts.  He packs some more stuff but he will tell me when I get there.  How many more items that he packed will fit into his luggage?<n>Output: The he is going to put some more items in his luggage.<n>He has 5 pairs of long, three pairs of shorts and five pairs of socks.<n>If each pair of socks are 1, then 5+3+5=<<5+3+5>>13 items will fit in his luggage<n><n>Input:  I have 18 items in my kitchen and 5 items in the cupboards.  When I go to buy items for my kitchen I buy doubles of all the cups, bowls, and plates I have in the kitchen.  I also buy enough foreknow I need for the 20 days.  How many more days do I need to buy for a total of 18 foreknow?<n>Output: I buy 5 foreknow for each item,  This results in 5+5+5...5=<<5+5+5....5=25>>25<n>I have 25 foreknow,I have to buy another 13=<<25+13>>38<n>So the final answer: 38<n><n>Input:In the town library, the number of books on the shelves is 5 less than 3 times the number of books on sale.  How many books are on sale?<n>Output:The total number of shelves is 3<times, this gives us,<2,2,2><n>The number of books on each shelf is <<>>=3,3,3<n>Therefore the number of books sold is <<5<*3,3,3>>=<15>>,<15>books<n>So the final answer : <40>>40<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where do farmers keep toothpicks? Choices:  A: mouth B: grocery store C: constructing models D: shed E: box<n>Output:		farmers keep tooth picks in the 'g'<n><n>Input: Find the first letter 'A' in the word 'Mandarin'.<n><n>Output: The "A" is at the first position<n><n>Input: The first 2 letters in the word 'MATH' are 'M' and 'A'.<n>In the first character 'M' a 'T' has been replaced by 'H'. What is the second letter?<n>Output: The second letter is 'A'<n><n>Input: What are 4, 4, 5, 13, and 41?<n>Output: 4 x 4 = 16<n>16 + 5 = 21<n>21 * 13 = 263<n>263 ** 4 = 2,104,292<n><n>Input: Write a computer program to determine the prime factors of a number.<n><n>Output: n = 48<n>n = 24 x 2<n>Output: <n><n>Input: If a clock shows 2 o’clock what time is 1:30?<n>Output: <n>If a clock has the time 2pm, then 130 is 1:3<n><n>Input: What can you say about the output of a subtraction expression like 3+4-7?<n>Output: 3+4–7 = 3–7 = -4<n><n>Input: What would the output of the expression 0 or 1 be?<n>Output: 0 or 1 would be 0<n><n>Input: Which expression is greater: 0 or 5–0?<n>Output: This expression is 5-0 which is less than 5 and so it is a greater than statement<n>The expression is actually less than - which is positive, so the answer is less than.<n><n>Input: What is the output of the subtraction expression 3-3-13-13?<n>Output: The expression 3-3–13–13 would equal 0-0-13–13.<n><n>Input: If 4-1=3, what would 5-2=?<n>Output: 6<n><n>Input:(Roses are)<n>Red<n>Pink<n>(Or are)<n>Green<n>Cream<n>Yellow<n>Orange<n>Input: (Motor vehicles

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where would you find some swords in your house? Choices:  A: sheath B: sword closet C: collection D: container called scabbard E: museum<n>Output:		The scabbard container is an E<n><n>Input: The scabbard is one of the containers that a sword is kept in when it is not actually being used. The Scabbard container, often called a sheath, contains an E<n><n>Output: The answer is E since Scabbard is an E.<n><n>Input: The sword container, usually called a sheath, keeps the E safe from damage when it is being stored.  How would you keep a scabbard organized? Choices: A: in the dirt B: clean C: with weapons D: with a sword E: in many places.<n>Output: The best answer is E because the scabbard is usually in many places in your house.<n><n>Input:  A sword is kept inside a sheath but the sheath may also be called a scabbard. How would you keep a chainsaw organized?  Choices: A: on the roof B: on the ground C: in the trunk D: in the tool shed E: on a stand<n>Output: The best option is E since chainsaws are usually on a stand and not other places in the house.<n><n>Input :What does a sword do? Choices: A:) cleave B:) pierce C:) thrust D: cleave, pierce, and thrust E: none<n>Output: Swords can do cleave, pierce and thrust, so E.<n><n>Input : Choose from the following definitions.  What kind of sword is a rapier? Choices: A : the rapier is a type of sword called a sabre B: the rapier is not a sword C: the rapier is often called a fighter D: the rapier is called a cutlass E: the rapier is usually an epee<n>Output: C since the rapier is not called a sword, but sometimes a sword and shield.<n><n>Input: A: a sword is an item that slices and sometimes a sword and shield B: a sword is defined as a kind of tool used for fighting  C: a sword comes from the Chinese word chun which means something made from iron D: a sword is a very long spear that slices someone like a big knife E: a sword is defined in two ways in one book and three ways in another E: a sword is a long sharp spear C: a sword is longer than a long knife  F: a
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Bill did not abandon the fight, but did what to the enemy? Choices:  A: arrogate B: retain C: embrace D: smile E: engage<n>Output:		The only choices that can complete the sentence is retire (A)  or engage (E):<n>So the final answer to question number one is B<n><n>Input: What did one computer engineer say to another? What did one chef say to another? Choices:  C: Bless you. E: Coffee's for you.   A: Happy birthday. D: Enjoy your coffee<n>Output: Happy Birthday is not a computer term and cannot be a valid answer.  The only other choice that a computer person might say is 'Coffee is for you':<n>So the final answer for number two is D<n><n>Input: What is the difference between an elephant and a fisherman? Choices: A: They do not have the same number of children. B: An elephant is very large. C: An elephant always swims. D: An elephant does not have a fisherman's problem<n>Output: The choices for this are:  A (An elephpant does not have the same number as a fisher)  C (Always Swims) which is not a real option<n>A fisherman would not have the same problem as an elephant because a fisherman is a fisherman but the elephant does not swim and therefore the problem does not apply to elephants.<n>So the final option is C<n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Billy went away because his parents were fighting and he didn't want to stay where? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where could you find a fox hunting when not in a forest? Choices:  A: open meadow B: arctic tundra C: beach D: great outdoors E: england<n>Output:		A and B<n><n>Input: John has 1 pair of skis, 1 helmet and 1 snowboard. How many skis does he need?<n>Output: He only has 100 skis<n><n>Input: John is working at the ski lift and sees a skier who has 20 ski tips. Ski tips are worth 10 cents each and he also has 500 skis. He plans to sell all his ski tips and buy a new ski lift ticket. The skier needs 5 ski lifts and will pay exactly the same price to get back up the hill as on the way down. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Lindy was a senior.  He lived with his children because he didn't want to go where? Choices:  A: republican party B: old people's home C: office D: park E: high school or college<n>Output:		Option A: He did not want to go to the republican party because it was not welcoming to younger people<n>Option B: He does not want to go to an old people's home because it is too depressing<n>Option C: He does not want go to an office because he doesn't like the cubicles<n>Option D: Lindy does not want to go the park because all the kids and adults would stare at him<n>Option E: Because he does not want to be surrounded with children or other kiddos<n>So the final answer Lindy would like to be with those who have left their parents and would enjoy being with other kids<n>So the final answer his high school<n><n>Input: Aaron, Ben and Cary are arguing and trying to argue who wins.  How many people are arguing?<n>Output: There are three (3) people involved in the argument<n><n>Input: What is the opposite of a day? He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:The rowdy frat boys shouted they would have fun and do what tonight? Choices:  A: do enjoy B: get laid C: enjoyable D: work less E: enjoy living<n>Output:		You can do a math function to solve this question. For example,<n>(fun and do what)*(shouted they would have fun) = <<fun and do what * shouted they would have>>4fun and do what * have fun<n>The choices are A:  fun and do what *  fun D: do what *  fun<n>There are a different number of letters in each choice.<n>A has 5 and 5 letters respectively.<n>D has7 and 4 letters respectively.<n>We can solve this math problem using the following equation: (fun and do what)=<<do what*fun>>5  So the final answer will be 5, which is D<n><n>Input: What 5 digit number is divisible by 7, and its last digit is 3? He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:There was a show on television about a ranger who loved flowers, but the next day it was about a gardener who also loved flowers. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:They wanted to eat at home but the cupboards were barren, so they had to go what? Choices:  A: cook dinner B: eat C: go back to work D: make food E: get food<n>Output:		After they ran out of food, they went to the store to:  A: make food, B: get food, C: eat, D: cook dinner<n><n>Incorrect Answer: Choices:  A-> B: eat,B: get food ,C: cook dinner,D: make food<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65. You offered him $12 per hour to work at your party, and he accepted. You then offered him $20 per hour for a 1-hour performance at someone's house and an extra $40 per hour for an outdoor performance. You told the clown that he would only have to perform once for the additional $40. During your bachelorette you gave him 2 hours of work and he was paid $20 per hour. Your friend told you she received a 1-hour show at her house for $100 plus $50 to perform in the front yard. How much did she pay in total?<n>Output:  We offer the clown $12 to work at the bachelorette = <<12>>$12<n>We offer $20 for 1 hour and $40 for any extra = <<20>>$20 for hour(1) and the extra =<<40>>$40 the same as 2 hours<n>We pay $20 for 2 hours at the party = <<20>>20 + 20 = 20 + 2 = 22<n>She paid $100 + extra ($50)=<<125>>125<n>So the final answer = <<125>> = 125<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. Choices:  A: town B: carpeting C: city D: phone book E: magazines<n>Output:		A bookstore<n><n>```R<n>bookstore<-read.csv("bookstore.csv")<n>bookstore<-gsub("_","\\\\_","bookstore.csv") # add in the \\ character to avoid an error after reading in the csv file<n>bookstore<-gtools::strsplit(bookstore,"\\") #use strsplit from gtools R package to split words in the csv file from a single cell.<n>answer<-as.numeric(bookstore[3]) #the 3 in brackets indicates that the correct answer should be the 3rd column in the.csv file<n>```<n><n>I found that the "gtools" package was helpful in the last step when I converted the data into the appropriate format (the \ character at the start). Here I tried using a few different libraries like "forcats" "readr" and "tidyr."<n><n>### Reference:<n>[Instruction 1](https://www.khanacademy.org/math/cc-sixth-grade-math/cc-6th-decimals/cc-6thfractionsdecimals-new/a/solving-story-problems-with-decimals-and-fractions)<n>[Instruction 2](https://www.mathsisfun.com/decimals/dollar-store.html)<n>[Instruction A](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8rK4qHUO6oA&feature=youtu.be)<n>[Instruction B](https://youtu.be/xuL3r3G_rZw)<n>[Instruction C](https://www.toppr.com/discover/question-bank/cbse-1/mathematics/solve-the-problem-with-rational-numbers/)<n>[Instruction D](https://www.codecademy.com/courses/learn-html-and-css/lessons/learn-html-tables)<n>[Instruction F](https://youtudeo.com/watch?t=41&v=r-zZXQ60sKc)<n>[Instruction G](https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/screent)<n>[Instruction H](https://www.learnthenumbers.

Choices:  A: build family together B: fall in love C: make love D: complete E: distance themselves<n>Output:		If the lover wants to build a family, they might want to A: build a family together<n>If the lover wants to fall in love, they might want to B: fall in love<n>If the lover makes love, they might want them to: C: make love<n>If the lovers do complete anything, they might want to D: complete together<n>So, if they distance themselves, then they might want to E: distance themselves with their partner<n>So the final answer must be either A: build family together, B: fall in love or E: distance themselves.<n><n>Instructions:<n><n>A: Enter in one of the answers above in the "question" field. <n><n>B: Go to the next prompt.<n><n>Answer: If the lover is a robot and wants to build a family with their lover, what would it do to build this family?<n><n>Answer: If they are on a date, what might happen?<n><n>Answer: Does a lover fall in love if they build a family?<n><n>Answer 2:<n>Can a lover fall in "love" with more than one lover?<n><n>Answer 3:<n>Can a lovers fall in love to build a family together?<n><n>Answer 4:<n><n><n>Can the family live together?<n><n>Answer:<n>If a lover builds a family, are they still a lover?<n>Input: Which animal would the lover most want to date? Choices:  an ostrich  a chicken a lion a rabbit<n>Output: An ostrich<n>If a lover wants to date an ostrich, they might have to find its beak to get its attention<n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where would you get a bag after someone fills it with clothes? How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:while luck plays a big role, every person who is great at something has focus and what to it? Choices:  A: hatred B: surprised C: compliments D: dedication E: solutions<n>Output:		Great people are obsessed with solving problems. A and E are possible answers but they don't accurately describe these people.<n>Answer Choice: B: dedicated and dedicated is something to strive for and what the greatest people have in common.<n><n>Input: If it takes x seconds to bake a cake in the oven and two times longer to cook spaghetti then which of the following could take the longest to cook? Choices: <n>A: a cake <n>B: a bowl of spaghetti <n>C: one bowl of spaghett<n>Output: You can double the time it takes to cook one item and the time it takes to bake another, but if it takes more than x seconds to bake one cake it won't take any longer than x seconds to cook one bowl of spagetti.<n>Hence, the longest time it takes to cook is x seconds.<n><n>Input: What is the greatest common factor of each of these numbers? Choices: 1, 4, 24, 120<n>5, 10, 30, 60<n>Output: GCF or greatest common factor. The GCF between each set of two numbers is the largest multiple they both have.<n><n>Input: Which animal of the following animals is most closely related to the lion: the bull, alligator, giraffe, tiger, mouse, rabbit, or penguin?<n>Output: It is easiest to determine similarities in their family trees to answer this.  The answer is either the rabbit, mouse, tiger, or penguin.  Of these, a mouse and penguin are not mammals.  It is easiest to choose based on if any of the animals belong to the same class (mammal) and if the species (lion, rabbit, etc) are in the same taxonomy.<n><n>Input: How many whole numbers are between 1 and 72?<n>Output: The prime factorization of 72 is 2^2 * 3^4.  Each number below 72 can be factored as a prime or product of primes. There are 3 numbers in this set whose prime factorization has 2 and 3 and every number is above 1.  The number below 72 with a prime factorization is 42.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. So in total there is 1 intersection or crossroad between Districts 4 and 6.<n>If you travel due west from District #6 on a road for a 1 mile, you will reach County District 5 on the map.  If you go 1 mile in the other direction (due east to District #7), it will also put you in District 5.  Traveling north from District 6 will put you into Mesa County at a later point.<n>So to sum it up,  you need to go East or West 2 miles in order to reach a county line because 2 miles is equal to one county line. So the final answer is 2:<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Which effect of stress could cause death if not treated immediately? Choices:  A: age grieving person B: heart attacks C: depression D: hair loss E: headache<n>Output:		Heart attacks occur due to stress.  It is the most lethal and immediate because it may lead to a heart failure. <n><n>

Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:A person takes a seat to watch a movie, where is he? Choices:  A: in cinema B: at the park C: martorell D: jeep E: airplane<n>Output:		A=<<mart>>mart<n>B=<<jeep>>jeep<n>C=<<park>>park<n>D=<<cinema>>cinema<n>E=<<airplane>>airplane<n>So the final answer does not contain any letter<n><n>Input: There are 4 types of animals living in farm.  Farm can be found at A, B, C, or D.  Choices A, B, C and D correspond to the 4 types of animals.  There are 4 pairs of animals and 3 pairs of pumps.  Animals that produce milk are in group A.  Animals that give their milk in pairs are in group B.  Animals that are kept in pairs are in group C.  Animals that cannot produce milk are kept in group D.  Choices: A: cow B: goat C: horse D: dog<n>Output: A=cow<<cow>>cow<n>B=cow<<cow>>Cow<n>C=cow<<horse>>horse<n>D=<<dog>>dog<n>So the final answer contains only letters A and B<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the question.<n><n><n>### Instructions:<n>### Solution: <n>```java<n>public class Solution {<n><n>  public boolean mySurroundedDiv2(char[][] board, String value) {<n>    boolean[] hasValue = new boolean[board.length]; <n>    boolean[] hasXValue = new boolean[26];  <n>    <n>    for(int i = 0; i<board.length; i++)<n>      if(i>0 && i<board.length-1&&board[i].charAt(i)==value)<n>        hasValue[i] = true;  <n>    for(int j = 1; j<board.length; j++)<n>      if(board[j].charAt(j-1)==value)<n>          hasValue[j] = true;<n>    for(int k = 2; k<value.length(); k++)<n>    {<n>      for(int i = hasValue.length-1; i>=1; i--)<n>        if(board[i-1].charAt(i-1)==value.charAt(k-2))<n>          hasXValue[value.charAt(i-k+1)-'a'] = true;

He could see clouds when he looked out his window.  Where might he live? Choices:  A: in books B: radio station C: city D: tower E: medieval castle<n>Output:		His description would be consistent with him living at a tower.<n>If he lives at a medieval castle, he wouldn't have a window.<n>If he lives on a radio station, he couldn't see clouds.<n>If he lives in a book, the clouds are not clouds.<n>If he lived in a city, he'd see many clouds but we don't know how many.<n>If he lives above a radio station, he wouldn't see clouds or have a window.<n>So the answer is Tower (B)<n><n>Input: If a train that can be at one of three different stations at 3:02 and leaves the station for another station at 3:07, what time will the train depart its second station?<n>Output: Since we know it will leave the station at 3:17, it must arrive on the 5:02 train at 4:07.<n>It's 5 minutes later than the last train that would get it there, which leaves at 4:02.<n>There must be at least one or more minutes between the last train to get it and the 5:00 train leaving at 4:00 to get there, meaning the 4:02 train is the earliest train that can get it there.<n>So the answer from this is 4:02<n><n>Input: A and B can agree on the name of only one of their friends.  They can't agree on all the names.  How is this possible? Choices: 1: One person is named C and one person is named D.<n>Output: Both of them are named C.<n>One of them is named D for sure: they can't agree on any other name than the other person's name.<n>So C and D are the names they're both disagreeing on.<n><n>You might think they're both named D because they can agree on one name, but they would have agreed on C to begin with.<n>So, the answer to this question is they are both named C.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:If one sees a fox and is standing in a coastal, gulf state, where is this person? Choices:  A: alabama B: louisiana C: south carolina D: arkansas E: mountains<n>Output:		A, because since you are seeing a fox and you are in a coastal/gulf state. Only the southern states fall under the category of A.<n><n>### Instruction:The next three programming exercises are a sequence of questions that test you on two major programming features: loops and functions.<n><n>### Question 1: Functions<n>Write a function that is called "sumSquareNumbers", where the sum of the first 10 even numbers is returned. The function will be called in the main as follows:<n><n>```<n>sumSquareNumbers(10);  //10 elements are provided as input<n>```<n><n>### Question2: Loops<n><n>Write a function called "primes"where the primes less than and including 100 are returned.  Then in its definition you can add a second argument to the function that you can optionally pass to a main function as follows:<n><n><n>```<n>sumPrimesTo100(2);    //2 elements to pass to sum primes function are passed<n>```<n><n>##  Programming Exercise: Exam Day Questions (Harder)<n>### Question 3: Loops<n>Write a function that adds the numbers 0 through 100, that is, it counts up. At the end if a special case is reached that will add the total count and return it to the caller of the function. Then in its definition you should add a second argument that is a 2-element array that contains a special value such as "<100 "in addition to the 0 and 100 numbers to represent the end condition. So calling the function like the following should return the total sum for the given input array:<n><n>```<n>var sumTo100=addNumbers(5, arrTo100);<n>```<n>### Question 4: Loops<n>Write two functions.  The first function adds the numbers 1 through 10 using a function whose name you give to the calling function. The calling function adds another, arbitrary number to it and then passes that argument in to the called function that it just called.  So the function will be:<n><n>```<n>const sumNumbers=((arr) => {<n>    var sumNumbers=0;<n>    for(x=0;x<arr.length;x++){<n>        sumNumbers+=arr[x];<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:A person writes a check to a clerk, where does the clerk put them? Choices:  A: cash register B: desk drawer C: pay envelope D: throw away E: box<n>Output:		They put it in the pay envelope<n><n>Input: A person writes a check to their friend and another person writes a check to the clerk, where does their friend put their check? Choices:  a: A B: D c: E d: B f: A  G: D h: B<n>Output: Their friend puts the check in the pay envelope with their own check<n><n>Input: In what year was the first movie made?<n>Output:  Choices: Choose the letter closest to the year.<n>c: 1911<n>g: 1927<n>a: 1930<n>b: 1948<n>n: 1955<n>h: 1970<n>Choose: 2*n+g=4<2*n+2=4><n>Output: The correct answer 1927 but you guess 4<n><n>Input:  There were 1,380 books stacked on the shelves.  There were 16 more books on the shelf than on the floor.  How many different ways can three stacks of books be formed?<n>Output: Choices : 1. There were 16 books on the floor. 2. There were 4 books on the floor.<n>a. One way 4 ways<n>b. 2 ways 0 ways<n>c. 1 way 0 ways<n>a>4<n>b.b<n>Output: The correct A but you guessed C<n><n>Input: In a bookstore in England, each book costs 100 dollars and there are 8 different books. How much did the books weigh together?<n>Output: Choice: 8 books = 800<n>a: 400<n>b: 0<n>c: 1000<n>Choices : d. 4000<n>Output: The correct a and you guess 800<n><n>Input: I made 26 cookies.  I divided the cookies into sets of four and set three in the refrigerator.  I gave my little sister two sets.  One set of cookies was set aside for my mother.  One set of 13 cookies.  What is the set aside for my mother?<n>Output: 13 cookies<n>a-a<n>b-e<n>c-d<n>e-q

The dessert price is one and a quarter times the milk price.  The milk price is one and a fourth times the main dish price. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:He was looking for the holiday decorations and found an old box of clothes up where? Choices:  A: attic B: trash C: loft D: closet E: box<n>Output:		The answer is B<n><n>Input:What's the difference between 45+10 and 35-9?A:20+<-3<n><<20+<-3>=-27>>The answer is A.<n>I think of 45+1 is 45+1=46<<4-6=4-6>>44<n>35-9 = 35-9=-44<<6+4=24>>24<n>So the answer is A<n><n>Input:I am making an apple pie. His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where are you likely to find a paper program? Choices:  A: theater B: computer C: opera D: television E: concert<n>Output:		The best place to find a concert program would be at a music concert.<<B>> B<n>The best place to find a ballet would be at a theater.<<A>> A<n>The best place to program theater would be on a computer.<<C>> C<n>The best place to watch opera would be on TV.<<D>> D<n><n>Output: The best places to watch an opera or ballet would be at the opera or ballet.<<D, A>> D, A<n>The best places to see theater would be at the theater or on a computer.<<A, C>> A, C<n>The best places to watch a concert would be at a concert or on TV.<<E, D>> E, D<n>So the correct answer is D, A, C, E, D<n><n>Input: There are a lot of different types of pizza.  They can have cheese, pepperoni, green peppers, green olives, mushrooms, sausage, and anchovies.  But a mushroom is different than a pepper.  There's no anchovies here.<n>Output: A green onion is NOT the same as a mushroom.<<NOT>>NOT<n>There's a huge difference between a sausage and a pepperoni.<<SAUSAGE-PEPPERONI>>SAUSAGE-PEPERONI<n>But a mushroom is somewhat like a pepper.<<ALMOST-PEPPER>>ALMOST-PEPER<n>Mushrooms, pepperoni and green olives are very different from each other.<<MUSHROOM-PEPPERON-GRLOL>> MUSHROOM-NOT-PEPPERON<n>But sausage is very similar to pepperoni.<n><<SAUSAGE-NOT-PEP>><n>Sausage and green olives are a great pairing as a topping.<<SAUSAGE.GRLOL>>SAUSAGE<n>Pepperoni is usually much spicier than green olives and pepper.<<PIP-GOL>><n>The cheesiest thing is definitely cheese.<<CHEESERY>>CHEESERY<n>Peppers and green olives are pretty tasty.<<PER.GRLOL>>PERRLOL<n>A green onion and a red pepper is a very spicy pizza to
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Billy bounced the ball off the wall. A table is not an accurate reflection of the object for a ball to bounce.  A toy box is an object that the player can bounce the ball towards.<n>A player can "play" in a park where he can roll, bounce, and throw to the ball. A closet is another play area. If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:If they were celebrating the occasion, how could the occasion be described? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:A musician is most likely to perform a concerto for clarinet with what type of group? Choices:  A: music store B: orchestra C: jazz band D: rock band E: music studio<n>Output:		A music store<n><n><n>#### Part of A:<n><n>When it was first published, Mozart's Symphony No. 40 contained two movements — a fast movement and a slow one (minuetto and andante). That was then followed by an insertion of a minuet in D major and finally another minuet. When it was revised a few years later, Mozart added a second movement, a slow movement, and two repeats of the beginning minuet and a closing finale, giving it the typical three movements that a symphony should have.<n><n>Another Symphony by Mozart that we like is Symphony No. 36 (“Linz”). Of his first edition, he added a minuet in the third movement and the minuet from the first movement was replaced by a new minuet. In the next edition, he added another movement (a slow movement), which gave it the typical three movements and a final repeat of the opening minuet and finale that made up the last movements.<n><n>#### Part of B:<n><n>Lady Gaga wrote the song “Poker Face” with the working title, “F*****g With You”, after watching an episode of the series The Hills. The song became a number-one hit in 20 countries and has sold more than 10 million copies worldwide.<n><n>The song “Just Dance” by Lady Gaga and Colby O’Donis was inspired by the scene in the 1996 movie “Mighty Ducks II”.<n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where will a native lemur be found? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Johnny and bill fought over money.  Johnny wanted it to be over.  What might he choose to do? Choices:  A: control people B: settle everything C: buy food D: increase power E: kill bill<n>Output:		 E: kill bill  <n><n>Choose B if you are 6 years or older<n><n>### 10 points<n><n>What is the name of the 1000th prime number (prime means divisible only by itself)?<n><n>### 20 points<n><n>What are the first 5 digits of the largest number you can make with 308502840 digits in it?<n><n>### 30 points<n><n>Write a program that takes a string representing a coordinate as in X Y and prints an appropriate capital letter on the correct square on the coordinate system. If the number ends in 0 (zero), you must treat it like it just had a 1 in front of it. For example, 80 would be interpreted as 81, and 92 would be interpreted as 9A. Print the letter correctly aligned with the first letter of the last word in the string. For example, the string X Y Z, would output “A X B Z” (the “C” will be left out, of course).<n><n>### 40 points<n><n><n>Create an integer variable, a, and use it to represent a 4 digit year (e.g. 19XX, 1990). ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:The man took 3 hours every morning for grooming, what is the likely result with his job? Choices:  A: tardiness B: looking good C: injury D: vacation E: neatness<n>Output:		If he is taking 3 hours every day, the job is likely a hair cut. If he is doing hair cut every day, he can't be getting many appointments for grooming. He probably also will get injured or get vacations.<n>So in your scenario, the most likely answer would be vacation which is D.<n><n><n>

He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What is likely to happen to someone's speech after becoming inebriated? Choices:  A: regret B: automobile accidents C: drunk driving D: talking nonsense E: talk intelligently<n>Output:		There is a correlation between being inebriated and talking nonsense<n><n>Input:Whenever I go to a party, I have a good time talking with all of my friends.  But the day after the party, I have a headache and feel tired.  What might be a cause of my headache? Choices: A: dancing B: loud music C: chatting with friends D: smoking E: all of these Choices A, B, C, and D<n>Output:  My headache could be caused by the loud music, smoking, and all of these.<n><n>Input:You want to make your own smoothies at home, and you buy a blender that claims to be "BPA free."  What does the acronym "BPA" stand for as in this context for choosing this type of blender? Choices:  - not suitable for refrigeration  - not safe to use when pregnant - biphenol A Choices A, B and C<n>Output: BPA in this context stands for biphenol A<n><n>Input:I am shopping for a new shirt and I found a sale. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What gets rid of a mundane routine? Choices:  A: sophisticated B: imprevist C: arcane D: heavenly E: new<n>Output:		A new idea is the answer to the question: What gets rid of a munam routine. <n><n><n>### Instruction:Answer the question(s).<n><n><n><n><n><n>

His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:The movie had many a song and dance, it was a what? Let's say x=8 and y=10, then 8 modulo 10 will equal 2. So 8 and 1,0, 8 and 2, and 8 and 5 all share the same modulo.<n><n>Input: A new species of sea slug is discovered by scientists to have two heads.
